<subSubSection box="[151,693,607,631]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,693,607,631]" box="[151,693,607,631]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis box="[151,291,607,631]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Etymology. –</emphasis>
An allusion to the form of the rachis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[151,481,647,671]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,764,647,710]" box="[151,481,647,671]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis box="[151,265,647,671]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Ecology. –</emphasis>
Terrestrial in forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[151,764,686,710]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,764,647,710]" box="[151,764,686,710]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis box="[151,320,686,710]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Distribution. –</emphasis>
Known from Colombian Chocó only.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="109" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[113,764,726,879]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis box="[151,237,726,750]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Notes. –</emphasis>
This species is unique in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[611,731,726,750]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Palmorchis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[611,731,726,750]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Palmorchis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its fractiflex rachis. It is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[615,756,759,783]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Palmorchis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pandurata">
<emphasis box="[615,756,759,783]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">P. pandurata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but its epichile is entire, transversely elliptic, obtuse and lip callus consists of 3 lamellae running from lip base to the apex, being highest in the upper part.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
